-------------------------------------------------------------
SECTION 3: CONTROL FLOW (NODE.JS FOCUSED)
-------------------------------------------------------------

3.1 Conditional Statements (if, else if, else)
----------------------------------------------
Syntax:
if (condition) {
   // code if true
} else if (anotherCondition) {
   // code if second condition true
} else {
   // code if none true
}

Example:
let age = 20;
if (age >= 18) {
    console.log("Adult");
} else {
    console.log("Minor");
}

-------------------------------------------------------------

3.2 Switch Statement
--------------------
- Useful when checking one value against many cases
- Includes "break" to stop execution

Example:
let role = "admin";
switch (role) {
    case "admin":
        console.log("Full Access");
        break;
    case "editor":
        console.log("Edit Access");
        break;
    case "viewer":
        console.log("Read-only Access");
        break;
    default:
        console.log("No role assigned");
}

-------------------------------------------------------------

3.3 Loops
---------
for loop:
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    console.log(i);
}

while loop:
let n = 0;
while (n < 3) {
    console.log(n);
    n++;
}

do...while loop:
let count = 0;
do {
    console.log(count);
    count++;
} while (count < 3);

-------------------------------------------------------------

3.4 Loop Control (break, continue)
----------------------------------
break → exits loop completely
continue → skips current iteration and continues

Example:
for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    if (i === 3) continue;  // skip 3
    if (i === 5) break;     // stop loop
    console.log(i);
}
// Output: 1, 2, 4

-------------------------------------------------------------

3.5 For-in and For-of
----------------------
for-in → iterate over object keys
for-of → iterate over iterable values (array, string, etc.)

Example with object:
const user = { name: "Ajay", age: 30 };
for (let key in user) {
    console.log(key, user[key]);
}
// name Ajay
// age 30

Example with array:
const arr = [10, 20, 30];
for (let val of arr) {
    console.log(val);
}
// 10, 20, 30

-------------------------------------------------------------
Good Practices
--------------
- Use if/else for conditions
- Use switch when many cases on the same variable
- Use for-of for arrays/iterables
- Use for-in for objects (but prefer Object.keys/Object.entries for clarity)
- Always include "break" in switch cases to avoid fall-through
-------------------------------------------------------------
